06802nam a22014415i 9781400836888DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20112011nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008368887 a10.1515/97814008368882doi  a(DE-B1597)446551  a(OCoLC)979754926  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJC153.L87bC38 2017 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.012231 aCasson, Douglas John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiberating Judgment :bFanatics, Skeptics, and John Locke's Politics of Probability /cDouglas John Casson.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. The Great Recoinage -- tI. Unsettling Judgment. Knowledge, Belief, and the Crisis of Authority -- tII. Abandoning Judgment: Montaignian Skeptics and Cartesian Fanatics -- tIII Reworking Reasonableness. The Authoritative Testimony of Nature -- tIV. Forming Judgment: The Transformation of Knowledge and Belief -- tV. Liberating Judgment: Freedom, Happiness, and the Reasonable Self -- tVI. Enacting Judgment: Dismantling the Divine Certainty of Sir Robert Filmer -- tVII. Authorizing Judgment: Consensual Government and the Politics of Probability -- tConclusion. The Great Recoinage Revisited -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamining the social and political upheavals that characterized the collapse of public judgment in early modern Europe, Liberating Judgment offers a unique account of the achievement of liberal democracy and self-government. The book argues that the work of John Locke instills a civic judgment that avoids the excesses of corrosive skepticism and dogmatic fanaticism, which lead to either political acquiescence or irresolvable conflict. Locke changes the way political power is assessed by replacing deteriorating vocabularies of legitimacy with a new language of justification informed by a conception of probability. For Locke, the coherence and viability of liberal self-government rests not on unassailable principles or institutions, but on the capacity of citizens to embrace probable judgment. The book explores the breakdown of the medieval understanding of knowledge and opinion, and considers how Montaigne's skepticism and Descartes' rationalism--interconnected responses to the crisis--involved a pragmatic submission to absolute rule. Locke endorses this response early on, but moves away from it when he encounters a notion of reasonableness based on probable judgment. In his mature writings, Locke instructs his readers to govern their faculties and intellectual yearnings in accordance with this new standard as well as a vocabulary of justification that might cultivate a self-government of free and equal individuals. The success of Locke's arguments depends upon citizens' willingness to take up the labor of judgment in situations where absolute certainty cannot be achieved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aJudgment (Logic). 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophyxHistoryy17th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aCounter-Reformation.  aEngland.  aFilmerian certainty.  aFirst Treatise.  aGod.  aGreat Recoinage.  aJohn Locke.  aMichel Montaigne.  aParliament.  aPierre Charron.  aReformation.  aRen Descartes.  aRobert Boyle.  aRobert Filmer.  aScripture.  aSecond Treatise.  aThomas Hobbes.  aTreasury.  aWilliam of Ockham.  aabsolutism.  aabstract speculation.  aapodictic science.  aauthority.  acertainty.  acivic education.  acivic judgment.  acontemporary liberal theo